  "prompt": "Where is the RAW filter in Photoshop CS6?",
  "response": "In Adobe Photoshop CS6, the RAW filter is called \"Camera Raw.\" To access the Camera Raw filter, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Open an image in Photoshop CS6.\n2. If the image is a RAW file (like .CR2, .NEF, .ARW, etc.), it should automatically open in the Camera Raw interface. You can make adjustments there before editing in Photoshop.\n3. If you want to apply the Camera Raw filter to a non-RAW image (like .jpg or .png), you can do so by following these steps:\n   - Select the layer you want to apply the filter to.\n   - Go to the top menu and select **Filter** > **Camera Raw Filter**. This will open the Camera Raw interface, allowing you to make adjustments similar to how you would with a RAW file.\n\nOnce you're in the Camera Raw window, you can adjust various settings such as exposure, contrast, clarity, and more. After you're done, click \"OK\" to apply the changes to your image in Photoshop.",
